<subsection xml:id="subsec-Properties-of-rotation">
    <title>Properties of Rotation</title>

    <p>
        In the figure 2.3.1 below, triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> is the image of triangle <m>PQR</m> under a transformation <m>R</m>
    </p>

     <figure xml:id="scalene-triangle">
        <caption></caption>
    <image source="/rotation-triangle2.png">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
     </figure>

    <p>
        We create <m>P'</m> the image of <m>P</m> by turning <m>OP</m> around point <m>O</m> by <m>90^\circ</m> in anticlockwise direction.
        The same process is applied to <m>Q</m>, resulting in <m>Q'</m>, and to <m>R</m>, generating its corresponding image.
        This consistent turning of points around a fixed center is called a rotation.
         In this case, point <m>O</m> is the centre rotation and angle <m>90^\circ</m> is the angle of rotation.
    </p>

    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Note:}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    A rotation in the anticlockwise direction is taken to be positive  i.e a rotation of <m>45^\circ</m> anticlockwise is <m>+45^\circ</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    A rotation in the clockwise direction is taken to be negative  i.e a rotation of <m>45^\circ</m> clockwise is <m>-45^\circ</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    In general, for a rotation to be completely defined, the centre and angle of rotation must be stated.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
